               <scopecontent id="aspace_c965a91def57347cf6019581562ccf08">
                  <head>Scope and Contents</head>
                  <p>Appointment is from the Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs.  At the time, Haran was associated with Barrington Hospital, Limerick, Ireland.</p>
               </scopecontent>
            </c>
            <c id="aspace_a699aa3d1d7d8ec460918602be210dbe" level="file">
               <did>
                  <unittitle>Report on Kismayu (copy)</unittitle>
                  <unitdate unitdatetype="inclusive">1901 October 27</unitdate>
                  <container altrender="archive legal tall"
                             containerid="39002010858000"
                             id="aspace_03baa359ba7718eea6541ecba1db3c4f"
                             label="Mixed Materials"
                             localtype="box">1</container>
                  <container id="aspace_19acf3ee17266ae4bd249591ad21be81"
                             localtype="folder"
                             parent="aspace_03baa359ba7718eea6541ecba1db3c4f">8</container>
               </did>
               <scopecontent id="aspace_e9ca11e4410472abc9adddf833d77c32">
                  <head>Scope and Contents</head>
                  <p>Kismayo or Kismayu is on the east African coast, now part of Somalia. Haran's draft report, typewritten with changes in ink, notes that he first arrived in Kismayu in August 1900. The report concerns mosquitos in Kismayu and public health work to reduce their numbers. Haran also discusses the care needed for health officers who become ill. He says he will be doing a report on the town of Yonte. With the report are contemporary copies of two letters to the Principal Medical Officer, East Africa Protectorate dated, 1901 November 3 and 11.</p>
               </scopecontent>
            </c>
