                  <p>Draft of a "confidential" report in ink, written in Nairobi (now the capital of Kenya), to be sent to the Secretary for Foreign Affairs and others</p>
               </scopecontent>
            </c>
            <c id="aspace_327a98379b4e6af0a65aa897836d2681" level="file">
               <did>
                  <unittitle>Letter from the Principal Medical Officer, East Africa Protectorate, congratulating the medical officers in Nairobi </unittitle>
                  <unitdate unitdatetype="inclusive">1902 July 5</unitdate>
                  <container altrender="archive legal tall"
                             containerid="39002010858000"
                             id="aspace_0b55092dc184f6d3ed9ba070476c4774"
                             label="Mixed Materials"
                             localtype="box">1</container>
                  <container id="aspace_4cc6917279283f2433353551861a1167"
                             localtype="folder"
                             parent="aspace_0b55092dc184f6d3ed9ba070476c4774">10</container>
               </did>
               <scopecontent id="aspace_a75cd7a4f86231e9f86a7d08ad5f9f59">
                  <head>Scope and Contents</head>
                  <p>Handwritten letter to the Medical Officers in Nairobi during the plague, Dr. J. A. Haran and Dr. William Radford, conveying congratulations from the Principal Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs "on the successful manner in which you combated the outbreak."</p>
               </scopecontent>
            </c>
